segments.text: At this point had the responsibility that I did when I was associate director, namely budgets and preparing requests to go to the legislature and essentially looking over the projects and lining up things.
Who did A&M's legislative work then?
Who were the key
Who were the key folks?
Bob Cherry.
Bob Cherry.
He worked the legislature and also was the right-hand man for the board?
That's right.
And did he keep you and others well informed?
Not really.
Did you as a new senior administrator get any
advice or direction or guidelines from board members or legislators or former students?
Not from former students, but from the legislators, yes, and from the board members, yes.
Can you mention some key people that attempted to give you guidance?
I think the board as a whole tried to give me guidance.
You see, at that particular point, we did something.
Patterson had really started it.

And that was to take this huge monstrosity or this huge mix of things that we had of stations out in the Experiment Station and convert them to a much smaller group, which he called Research and Extension Centers.
And when I was still associate director, I went up with Earl Rudder one day.
We used to call him the East Texas Pasture Research Station, Research Center, and this kind of a thing.
And that summer, a curious kind of
occurrence happened was that the Texas Sheep and Goat Raisers Association met.
And they there, they were at that time, maybe they still are, quite a resolutionizing group of people.
And so they resolved
And one of the resolutions was to give, criticize Texas A&M University and the university system very heavily for not being responsible to the sheep and goat raisers.
At the same time, they were very complimentary of the station out at San Angelo was doing the kind of work they were doing.
You see, what they were doing was they were not, in their minds, they were separating these stations from the main center.

So coming back from a visit with the folks at Monday, which was another political situation, Earl Runner leaned over to me and he says, why don't you call all of these people, why don't you call all these centers, Texas A&M Center, at so-and-so.
So I went back and drafted and had a secretary to do just the first draft of things.
And I said, is this what you mean?
He says, yeah, give it to me.
And before I knew it, the Board of Regents had approved all of these names.
So one fell swoop, it became Texas A&M University Research and Extension, Agricultural Research and Extension at Lubbock, Agricultural Research and Extension at this.
And so it was at this point that I decided, well, we were really going to put these things in place.
So I appointed a committee to go around to these various places, and I said, you know, we have problems of locations.
because the legislators in many aspects of the situation believe that these centers ought to be in the middle of the agricultural world.
And I wasn't quite sure about that, so I set this committee out and they came back and they said these centers need to be associated with cities, which I agreed with.
And the principal reason for putting these centers at these cities was that the faculty, we could hire reasonably good faculty if they could have reasonably good areas to live in.
But if they had to live in Chillicothe or some other outlying places, a few people like the range scientists and the animal husbandmen,
You could put out at those places, but agronomists, no.
You just were loaded.
So I decided we were going to locate.
Well, it...
became quite a football player at that point as we went along.
We were able to pick up the Renner Foundation, which is located in Renner, north of Dallas, and convert it to Texas A&M University Agricultural Research and Extension Center at Dallas.
And it's next door to the University of Texas at Dallas.

So from place to place we were able to establish and get people to give land, to get people to give money for our buildings, and you could put up a pretty good building for $200,000 in those particular days and time.
And the original location of all of these research units had been political long ago, wasn't it?
They were political long ago, and they remain political as far as this is concerned.
And the most political of the one was the one at U Valley which should have been at San Antonio and the one at Chillicothe which should have been at Wichita Falls.
Well, Dolph Briscoe was governor at that particular point and so the board decided
They took that away from me and decided we were going to move to U Valley.
And they said, you build it there and you build it in a hurry.
So I had a way of doing that.
I got the board to accept an architect that had been at another place.
And they said, you duplicate this building right here.
So you find now that the agricultural research and extension centers are across the state.
Probably as much of a political situation.
Now there's political visibility.
The one in Dallas now is completely surrounded by urban areas.
It's a green area.
And I'm assuming that the realities of that situation in Texas are very little different from any other state.
Wouldn't this be about the same in other states?
You mean the location?
Yeah.
There are no, this is the only state that has that kind of setup.
Oh, really?
Yes.
And that's actually, I think, one of my greatest achievements as an administrator.
Do we have more locations than per capita or fewer?
Well,
Probably so.
Probably more?
You see, California had some, and most of those eventually became University of California at so-and-so, and various places of that sort.
Florida had what they call A-R-E-C, agricultural research extensions.
My concept was that these need to be educational centers as well as research centers.
In that year before Mr. Rutter's illness, or two years, did you and O.D.
Butler and Mr. Rutter sometimes go to reserve meetings together?
Only
Only as the division met.
And that was how often?
Once a year.
Oh, okay.
Did you ever see, did Mr. Rutter have much of a sense of humor?
Did you ever see him?
I've heard him laugh, yes.
When did you see him really get angry over something?
Really unhappy?
I don't know that I ever did.
I did see him in action as a political person.
Oh, describe that.
And he went to, well there was a bit of money being made available to the Department of Interior for water research and the
enabling legislation nationally, sort of put it at the Land Grant University, but we had some trouble with the possibility that some of this stuff could go out to Texas Tech.
And so the legislature was, and the senator who had
built this, putting this bill in to move it someplace, Earl Rudder went down to see him, and you should have seen the shouting that went on in that one.
But that was the only time I'd ever seen or heard Earl Rudder shout.
And which board?
Senator Krueger, by the way.
Senator Krueger.
What about our local legislative delegation, Bill Moore and
and various state representatives.
Did you see them in action much during the Rutter years?
Yes.
Describe.
I think fundamentally Bill Moore was as much of a supporter of this university as any, and the fact is he didn't like for anything to be outside of this College Station Bryan.
And so anything here he
would, he would support anything away.
He would drag foot.
And did you work at all with Brownrick Dewey?
Yes, I had Brownie, yes.
He was quietly efficient, wasn't he?
Quietly efficient, yes.
Did you, in those, in the 60s, did any board member ever deal with you directly, or did they go through Mr.
Rudder appropriately?
They came at me directly.
Is that right?
Yeah.
What were their concerns?
Oh, usually small directions and this kind of a thing.
Did they ever try to tell you what to fund or who to appoint?
No.
They didn't get involved in the details?
They didn't get involved in the whole situation.
Did you go to board meetings in those, in the voter years?
I went to board meetings in those days.
And he, as a matter of fact, is the associate director of the station.
I went to the executive committee and Errol Rudder's executive committee meetings.
Describe those.
Who was at his executive committee meetings?
The four or five deans and two associate directors.
Were there minutes kept?
Were there votes taken?
I think so, I think so, but most of it you'd have people like Fred Benson.
We'd talk softly at him.
Patterson was pretty quiet.
Which of those individuals do you think Earl Rudder listened to most?
I'd say Fred Benson.
I would have been surprised if you had not.
Why was Benson so effective?
He was quiet and very logical.
Highly logical.
He and I, I enjoyed being with him as a co-dean, as a level, not as a co-dean, but at the same... Oh, oh, oh, I was trying to figure out what word you were saying.
You were saying as a fellow dean, yeah.
Fellow dean, is what I meant to say.
Was he your favorite colleague?
He had to be, yeah.
Did y'all ever get together socially, you deans and directors?
In the Earl Rudder days, yes.
In the Jack Williams days, yes.
And heads of departments used to get together socially.
We'd have social events when I was dean.
Where were they held?
At various homes, mostly.
Coat and tie?
Coat and tie.
Were alcoholic beverages served?
Sometimes.
I remember Fred Benson saying that when he first got here, if you served alcoholic beverages, you closed the shades.
Probably so.
In those, in the 60s, where did you and other couples, where did you all go eat, if you're going to eat, you're going to dine out?
Coach Norton's.
Okay.
Tom's.
At about that time, well in the 60s, about that time some of the clubs were being developed.
And what were the events on campus that you and your spouses normally attended?
Oh, student club banquets and things of the sort, particularly in April we were going.
And then, of course, our old rudder would have a dinner for somebody.
Did the rudders ever have a dinner for the deans and so forth at the old president's house?
I don't know.
I don't recall.
I don't either.
Did you as dean go to the Ag Ball?
Did faculty and students?
and administrators go to the boot dance and the ring dance and things like that?
We had invitations to all of them.
But did you go?
Oh, yes.
Oh, did you?
Okay.
Cotton ball, that's what I was trying to think of.
Cotton ball.
Now, that was a big event, wasn't it?
That was a big event.
Of course, that died under my years.
I finally killed it.
Well, it just withered away, didn't it?
It just withered away, yeah.
As in your first...

months or years of being of having these big responsibilities what were some of the first real difficult matters that you had to deal with the one you mentioned was the the the locations and all of that well political locations with the centers and things predominant things what about research topics and projects uh
I don't know that I dealt with them, but I don't know that it was considered a problem.
One of the things was that I became an administrator.
I decided that the College of Agriculture was going to have to move toward the scientific group.
And as we replaced faculty, we would move more and more into the scientific area.
I had some difficulty problems with finding somebody to head the Department of Biochemistry.
because I didn't know all of these situations.
Sometimes I find a difficulty of finding heads of departments moving in, particularly in some of these others.
We didn't use the committee system.
I found it very useful later on as far as the approach was concerned.
I lost a lot of confidence in the committee system when we

through the years, largely because they could be managed by people who had certain concerns and things of the sort, and sometimes you had to take over if you were going to change direction, you were going to have to do this through the head of the department.
In biochemistry, what were you hoping at the time you said the problem, what was the problem?
Well, the problem was to try to find somebody who could lead the department toward science and upgraded in science.
And we eventually, I eventually did this.
I did get a hold of Gene Santer, who is now Dean of Agriculture at the University of Arizona.
But Gene, he wasn't as strong a biochemist as the faculty would have liked and so forth.
But he did turn it around, and of course the Department of Biochemistry now is largely a molecular biology department.
And what has bothered me a little bit about the change is that the momentum, which I think I started, essentially ended up the legacy.
It was called the College of Agriculture and Life Sciences.
That was an interesting battle.
Describe that.
Well, of course, the people in science, Dean Fackler, I tried it for 20 years, and first I couldn't get my own faculty, my own heads of departments, essentially, to move in that direction.
And I'd propose ideas and get absolute results.
I'd drop them, and I'd come back a little bit later.
As we went into it, essentially, I had a decision that I was going to make this.
By that time, I was just dean.
I didn't have any responsibilities as far as Experiment Station or Extension Service was concerned.
And even Clark held a meeting of holding this kind of thing.
Richardson took a negativity to it, obviously.
Fackler didn't want it.
But things got so bad in the department of biology that they essentially were no longer supporting, the biologists were no longer supporting the dean of science.
And when I saw that happening, I immediately shoved it in.
Of course, that was the end of my career as dean.
Charlie Arnson carried on and it was made so the name Agriculture and Life Sciences and I have the title of Dean Emeritus, Agriculture and Life Sciences and Agriculture.
This is a note for the typist that you don't need to put in the typescript.
It's an attempt at dry humor at Missouri one day as they were talking about adding something like that to the title College of Agriculture.
with a straight face at a large gathering, I proposed that they consider renaming it Food, Agriculture, and Resource Management.
And then I asked them to consider what the acronym would be.
And a few people from across the state thought that F-A-R-M would be a very good.
All right, let's go back chronologically then
Mr.
Rudder becomes ill in early 1970.
Right.
Were you and your colleagues aware soon before his illness that he was?
I had no idea, as a matter of fact.
I had been on a foreign assignment, been out of the country.
I came back and I got a call in Chicago that Mr. Rutter wanted me to go to East Pakistan, Bangladesh.
And because our project was coming to an end there,
He wanted me to go, and then they told me he was in the hospital in Houston.
And that was the last we ever saw of him.
I never did see him after that.
So he sent, the last thing he did was send me to Asia.
Then we have a brief- By the way, I was not successful.
And I'll tell you why I wasn't successful.
And it should have given us a lesson to learn.
When we had the contract to improve the faculty at East Pakistan Agricultural University, we trained every one of those PhDs here.
And so what they got in was a bunch of Aggies against
the European-trained people, and the chancellor didn't want any more of that.
Or the vice chancellor, I should say.
Who was that?
That's the vice chancellor in the East Pakistan Agricultural University, the Bangladesh Agricultural University.
I thought you meant here.
I thought you meant here.
Mr. Rutter died.
We had a period of an interim president, and then Jack Williams is selected to begin in the fall of 1970, November the 1st.
Do you remember what your first reactions were to his appointment?
My first reaction was very positive.
As a matter of fact,
He came down after his appointment.
I was in the administration and he poked his head in my office and said, I'm joining you.
Describe, make believe I'd never seen him or known his personality, describe what he looked like and how he handled himself.
He behaved himself as a real academic.
I'm not sure I could describe his physiognomy.
He was clearly one who supported me as dean.
And I could go to him and we'd talk things over.
His office was right above mine.
I considered him tall.
Fairly lean.
Did he seem to understand the realities of agriculture far more than any other president has ever done since, including, well, I'm on your side.
I agree.
Did he ever smile?
Oh, yeah.
Sure.
Yes.
And did he make an effort, as far as you were aware, to learn about the realities of our agriculture programs?
Yes, because right in the middle of his career, right in the middle of his career as deanship, we were building these research and extension centers.
So I had to, of course, in days of early winter, he'd walk into the board meeting and say, yeah, I want one there here.
And gave a listing of where they ought to be.
But after that, it had to be far more formal in the approach, and he would help out.
But we would talk about these situations.
Did he, as far as you were aware, did he listen to you, did Williams listen to you and the other senior administrators?
I think so.
I think so.
What do you think his goals were for A&M?
What kind of school did he want this to be?
Well, I imagined and perceived that he wanted Texas A&M University to be a great university in the academic sense.
Was that consistent with what your goals were?
That was consistent with my goals.
What did you have?
And I think that the goals are still that.
The difference now compared to when I was there was the fact that I did not want to leave my roots in agriculture.
And I see we're now losing our roots in agriculture as an institution.
What were your, at that point, did you have any other institutions that you, in agriculture, that you were kind of using as your model?
Cornell.
Cornell.
Wisconsin.
Maybe Davis, Les Davis though.
When you, when you first took over as an administrator, about where do you think we honestly ranked in agriculture nationally?
Oh, I'd say below the bottom.
Not in the top ten.
And today?
And I think after today, well, it was in the top ten.
It was definitely four or five, maybe even higher than that, depending upon what you're looking at it.
And what were you asking?
And did you have any high priority
projects, programs that you wanted to get done?
Well, the highest priority project that I wanted to get done is essentially turn and get established molecular biology and what is known as biotechnology on the campus.
Where did you get the money for that?
Well, you stole it from other projects.
You just closed out other projects.
I did this thing in a very interesting way rather than doing as currently situations where you bring in the positions and then think about them and think of a sort and then redo this.

I had, in my own mind, established a thought of where we needed to go, and as a position occurred, if the head of department didn't dream for it, I took that position and put it in another department.
And during your years in that- Without saying anything, I didn't, I was very quiet.
I didn't have a committee or anything of the sort.
I just, it was more of a individual type of administration.
where you did what you wanted to do by changing the funding operation.
Who were the key people you turned to here on the campus and elsewhere for advice and counsel and opinions?
Well, I think the people that were around me in the administration.
Heads of departments.
Bill Pope.
Terry Greathouse when he came in.
At least I try ideas on them.
Various heads of departments.
Hobgood.
That's Merle Hobgood?
No.
What's his name?
Price?
Price Hobgood.
Price Hobgood.
And your key staff members at that time were, were whom?
Well I have, actually some of the key staff members would seem to be in and around, well it was O.D.
and there was Perry Atkinson and these people before they went up into administration were people that I would listen to.
The, and under Williams
In hindsight, so real progress is made, then, am I correct?
That's correct.
But you see, that was also the time in which the enrollment was increasing and the funding was increasing.
So there was the opportunity to develop because you had new programs and developing and then the growth of the university.
All right, and then Williams has a heart attack.
were you aware that he was in bad health no i surely wasn't either and i saw him on
